VALUES
(41, 5, 15, 51, 1, 13, 13, NULL, 'Deliverance from Darkness', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from evil. In Mark 5:15, the man is freed from demonic possession, while Colossians 1:13 speaks of being delivered from the power of darkness.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 55, 1, 7, 7, 'in his right mind', 'Fear and Sound Mind Connection', 'This connection highlights the transformation from fear to a sound mind. In Mark, the man previously possessed is now ''in his right mind,'' while 2 Timothy emphasizes that God gives us ''a sound mind'' instead of fear.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 9, 6, 20, 21, 'they were afraid', 'Fear of the Holy', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the presence of the divine. Both passages depict individuals encountering a powerful, holy presence and expressing fear in response to it.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 9, 16, 4, 4, 'they were afraid', 'Fear and Transformation', 'Both passages emphasize a reaction of fear in response to a significant transformation. In Mark, the healed man is found ''in his right mind,'' while in 1 Samuel, the elders tremble at Samuel''s arrival, indicating a profound change or presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 23, 49, 24, 25, 'in his right mind', 'Deliverance from Captivity', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from captivity. In Mark 5:15, the man is restored to his right mind, paralleling Isaiah 49:24-25, which speaks of captives being delivered from the mighty.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 41, 5, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Possession and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation of the man possessed by a legion of demons. In Mark 5:9, he identifies himself as ''Legion,'' while in Mark 5:15, he is found ''in his right mind'' after Jesus'' intervention.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 15, 42, 8, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Demonic Possession', 'Both passages emphasize a man possessed by devils. In Mark, he is described as ''clothed'' and ''in his right mind,'' contrasting with Luke''s description of him as ''ware no clothes.'' This highlights the transformation experienced after encountering Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 40, 8, 34, 34, NULL, 'Request for Jesus to Depart', 'Both passages emphasize the plea for Jesus to leave the area. In each instance, the people express a desire for him to depart from their coasts.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 41, 1, 24, 24, NULL, 'Rejection of Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and rejection of Jesus by those he encounters. In Mark 5:17, the people ask Jesus to leave, paralleling the demonic voice in Mark 1:24 that expresses a desire for separation from him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 42, 8, 37, 37, 'to depart out of their coasts', 'Request for Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the request for Jesus to leave the region. In Mark, the people pray him to depart, while in Luke, the multitude besought him to depart due to fear.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 1, 26, 16, 16, NULL, 'Request for Departure', 'Both passages emphasize a request for departure due to perceived threat or superiority. In Mark, the people ask Jesus to leave, while in Genesis, Abimelech tells Isaac to go because he is mightier.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 18, 21, 14, 15, NULL, 'Rejection of Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize a desire for God to depart. In Mark, the people plead for Jesus to leave, while in Job, they express a wish for God to distance Himself due to their rejection of His ways.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 41, 5, 7, 7, 'pray him to depart out of their coasts', 'Fear and Rejection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and rejection of Jesus by the people. In Mark 5:7, the demon acknowledges Jesus'' authority and expresses fear, while in Mark 5:17, the people plead for Him to leave, indicating their discomfort with His presence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 17, 42, 5, 8, 8, NULL, 'Fear and Departure from Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize a sense of fear and unworthiness in the presence of Jesus. In Mark, the people ask Jesus to ''depart'' due to fear, while in Luke, Peter requests Jesus to ''depart from me'' because of his sinfulness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 42, 8, 38, 39, 'that he might be with him', 'Desire to Follow Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the man''s desire to be with Jesus after his healing. In both accounts, he expresses a longing to accompany Jesus, highlighting the transformative impact of his encounter.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 50, 1, 23, 24, 'that he might be with him', 'Desire to Be with Christ', 'This connection highlights a shared desire to be with Christ. In both passages, the individuals express a longing to be in the presence of Jesus, emphasizing the value of that relationship.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 41, 5, 17, 17, 'might be with him', 'Desire for Presence', 'Both passages emphasize a desire for proximity to Jesus. The man possessed by a devil wishes to be with Him, while the people of the region ask Him to leave, highlighting contrasting responses to His presence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 19, 116, 12, 12, NULL, 'Response to Divine Benefits', 'This connection highlights the theme of gratitude and response to divine intervention. In Mark 5:18, the man seeks to follow Jesus after being freed from possession, while Psalms 116:12 questions how one can repay the Lord for His benefits.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 41, 5, 7, 7, 'possessed with the devil', 'Possession and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the interaction between Jesus and the possessed man. In Mark 5:7, the man, possessed by demons, recognizes Jesus'' authority, while in Mark 5:18, after being healed, he desires to follow Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 18, 42, 23, 42, 43, 'that he might be with him', 'Desire for Presence with Jesus', 'This connection highlights the desire to be with Jesus expressed in both passages. The man possessed by a devil wishes to be with Jesus, while the criminal on the cross asks Jesus to remember him, indicating a longing for closeness with Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 19, 66, 16, 16, 'tell them how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Proclamation of God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of declaring what God has done. Both passages emphasize sharing personal experiences of God''s compassion and great deeds.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 43, 4, 29, 29, 'tell them how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Sharing Testimonies of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of sharing personal experiences of Jesus'' compassion. Both passages emphasize the importance of telling others about the great things the Lord has done.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 23, 38, 9, 20, 'how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Healing and Testimony Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of recovery and the importance of sharing one''s experience of healing. In Mark, the healed man is instructed to tell others about the compassion he received, while Hezekiah expresses gratitude for his recovery and the need to proclaim God''s truth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 27, 4, 1, 3, 'how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Signs and Wonders of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of proclaiming God''s great deeds. Both passages emphasize sharing the compassion and wonders of the Lord with others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 27, 6, 25, 27, 'how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Divine Deliverance and Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of deliverance by God and the importance of sharing that testimony. In Mark, the healed man is instructed to tell others of God''s compassion, while in Daniel, King Darius proclaims God''s deliverance and power to all nations.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 44, 22, 1, 21, 'tell them how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Witnessing and Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of sharing one''s experience of God''s compassion and actions. In Mark, Jesus instructs the healed man to tell his friends about the great things done for him, while in Acts, Paul recounts his transformation and commission to be a witness to all men.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 19, 44, 26, 4, 29, 'tell them how great things the Lord hath done for thee', 'Witnessing and Sharing Testimony', 'This connection highlights the theme of sharing personal testimony about God''s actions. In Mark, the healed man is instructed to tell his friends about the great things the Lord has done, while in Acts, Paul recounts his transformation and mission to witness to others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
